Revenue prediction

Scenario

You are employed in a bank, present in many countries around the world. It wants to target new potential customers, especially young people of age to open their first bank account. However, it wants to target the prospects most likely to have high incomes later in life. Therefore the team you work with has been tasked creating a model to determine a person's potential income. "What information do we have?" you ask your supervisor who replies: "Actually ... almost none: only the parents' income, because we are going to target the children of our current customers, as well as the country where they live. Oh yes, one last thing: this model must be valid for most countries of the world. With so little data available, it seems like a big challenge! Thus, you propose a linear regression with 3 variables: parents' income, the average income of the country in which the prospect lives, the Gini index calculated on the incomes of the inhabitants of the country in question. Note : This project only deals with the construction and interpretation of the model. You will not go to the prediction stage

Imputation of Gini indexes¶

From the income of each quantile, we compute the Gini index for the countries whose Gini index is missing. The Gini index of a country is twice the area between the curve of the "perfectly egalitarian case" and the Lorenz curve associated with the country.
In [26]:
country_code_to_imput_gini = ['AZE','CAN','CHN','EGY','GHA']
country_name_to_imput_gini = ['Azebaijan','Canada','China','Egypte','Ghana']
color = ['b','r','g','y','orange','black','grey','brown','purple','pink']

# Plotting Figure
plt.figure(figsize = (15.5, 17))
for country_code,country_name, c in zip(country_code_to_imput_gini, country_name_to_imput_gini, color):
    # income_2008_total_country : Total revenue on the 100 percentiles
    income_total_country = data[data.country==country_code]['income'].sum()
    # lorenz : Lorenz curve
    lorenz = (np.cumsum(np.sort(data[data.country==country_code]['income']))/income_total_country)*100
    lorenz = np.append([0],lorenz)
    x = np.append([0],data[data.country==country_code]['quantile'])    
    plt.plot(x,lorenz,c,linewidth=6, label=country_name)
    
plt.plot([0,100],[0,100],'grey',linestyle='--',linewidth=2, label='Perfect egalitarian case')
plt.xlabel('Population quantile',fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
plt.ylabel('% accumulated income',fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
plt.xticks(fontsize=25)
plt.yticks(fontsize=25)
plt.legend(loc='upper left',fontsize=15)
plt.grid(True,linestyle='--')
plt.title('Figure 3 - Lorenz curve : Population and income',fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
plt.savefig('figure/Figure 3 - Lorenz curve : Population and income.png', dpi=300)
plt.show()

# calculation of Gini indices for each country whose index is missing
list_gini = []
for country_code in countries_missing_data:
    # income_2008_total_country : Total revenue on the 100 percentiles
    income_total_country = data[data.country==country_code]['income'].sum()
    # lorenz : Lorenz curve
    lorenz = (np.cumsum(np.sort(income[income.country==country_code]['income']))/income_total_country)*100
    lorenz = np.append([0],lorenz) # La courbe de Lorenz commence à 0
    
    aire_ss_courbe = lorenz[:-1].sum()/len(lorenz)
    S = 50 - aire_ss_courbe 
    value_gini = 2*S
    list_gini.append(round(value_gini,2))

Mission 2 - Data Analysis

a. Choice of countries to analyze

115 countries are present in Data. To analyze the data from an economic point of view, 5 to 10 countries are chosen from all countries. To select these 5 to 10 representative countries from all the countries, a clustering of 115 countries is carried out on the two "economic" variables: the average income of the country and the Gini index of the country.

    Random generation of parents' income class¶

    In [60]:
    import scipy.stats as st
from collections import Counter

def generate_incomes(n, pj):
# We generate the income of the parents (expressed in logs) according to a normal law.
# The average and variance do not affect the final result (ie on the cipher of the income class)
# Generation of n realizations of the variable ln (Yparent) according to a normal distribution
    ln_y_parent = st.norm(0,1).rvs(size=n)
    # Generation of a realization of the error term epsilon seloin a normal distribution of mean 0 and standard deviation 1
    residues = st.norm(0,1).rvs(size=n)
    # Ychild and yparent values are returned.
    return np.exp(pj*ln_y_parent + residues), np.exp(ln_y_parent)

# Calculation of the income class c_i_child and c_i_parents
# Associates a quantile with each child / parent in the list whose income ychild / yparent is known
def quantiles(l, nb_quantiles):
    size = len(l)
    l_sorted = l.copy()
    l_sorted = l_sorted.sort_values()
    quantiles = np.round(np.arange(1, nb_quantiles+1, nb_quantiles/size) -0.5 +1./size)
    q_dict = {a:int(b) for a,b in zip(l_sorted,quantiles)}
    return pd.Series([q_dict[e] for e in l])

# compute_quantile: Returns the dataframe containing by child, his income, that of his parents, his income class (quantile), that of his parents
def compute_quantiles(y_child, y_parents, nb_quantiles):
    y_child = pd.Series(y_child)
    y_parents = pd.Series(y_parents)
    c_i_child = quantiles(y_child, nb_quantiles)
    c_i_parent = quantiles(y_parents, nb_quantiles)
    sample = pd.concat([y_child, y_parents, c_i_child, c_i_parent], axis=1)
    sample.columns = ["y_child", "y_parents", "c_i_child","c_i_parent"]
    return sample

def distribution(counts, nb_quantiles):
    distrib = []
    total = counts["counts"].sum()
    if total == 0 :
        return [0] * nb_quantiles
    for q_p in range(1, nb_quantiles+1):
        subset = counts[counts.c_i_parent == q_p]
        if len(subset):
            nb = subset["counts"].values[0]
            distrib += [nb / total]
        else:
            distrib += [0]
    return distrib   

# Calculation of conditional distribution matrix of parents for each c_i_child
def conditional_distributions(sample, nb_quantiles):
    # for each income class of a child c_i_child we count the number of parents per income class c_i_parent
    counts = sample.groupby(["c_i_child","c_i_parent"]).apply(len)
    counts = counts.reset_index()
    counts.columns = ["c_i_child","c_i_parent","counts"]  
    # compute the conditional distribution matrix of c_i_parent for each income class c_i_child
    mat = []
    for child_quantile in np.arange(nb_quantiles)+1:
        subset = counts[counts.c_i_child == child_quantile]
        mat += [distribution(subset, nb_quantiles)]
    return np.array(mat) 

# Graphical display of the conditional distribution matrix
def plot_conditional_distributions(p, cd, nb_quantiles):
    plt.figure(figsize = (31, 17))
    # The following line is used to display a chart in "stack bars", on this model: https://matplotlib.org/gallery/lines_bars_and_markers/bar_stacked.html
    cumul = np.array([0] * nb_quantiles)
    for i, child_quantile in enumerate(cd):
        plt.bar(np.arange(nb_quantiles)+1, child_quantile, bottom=cumul, width=0.95, label = str(i+1) +"e")
        cumul = cumul + np.array(child_quantile)
    plt.axis([.5, nb_quantiles*1.3 ,0 ,1])
    plt.legend(fontsize=40)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=25)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=25)
    plt.xlabel("parents quantile",fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel("probability of the child quantile",fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
    plt.title("Figure - Conditional distributions : p=" + str(round(p,2)),fontsize=30,fontweight = 'bold')
    plt.savefig('figure/Figure - Conditional distributions : p='+ str(round(p,2)) +'.png', dpi=300)
    plt.show()

# For a parent, probability of belonging to a class knowing the class of the child and the coefficient of elasticity of the country
def proba_cond(c_i_parent, c_i_child, mat):
    return mat[c_i_child, c_i_parent]

pj = 0.9                 # elasticity coefficient of country j
nb_quantiles = 100       # number of quantiles (number of income classes)
n  = 1000*nb_quantiles   # sample size

# Generation of n realizations of the variable ln (Yparent) according to a normal distribution

The income class of the child is independent of the income class of the parents.

    Very low mobility: Coefficient of elasticity: 0.9¶

    In [63]:
    country_plot_conditional_distributions('PAN')
    For a country with a coefficient of elasticity of 0.9, mobility in terms of income class is very low. Graphically, we notice:
  • When the parents belong to the 1st quantile, the probability that the child remains in this quantile is 0.4, which is very high. In other words, there is a high probability that the child does not change the quantile and remains in that of his parents.
  • When the parents belong to the 10th quantile, the probability that the child remains in this quantile is 0.5, which is very high. In other words, there is a high probability that the child does not change the quantile and remains in that of his parents.
  • Between the 4th and 7th percentile, the odds of staying in the quantile of his parents, or of changing quantile ± 1, are similar.

    def repartition_class_children(n_quantile, frequences):
    c_k_children = []
    for i in range(len(frequences)):
        number_children_class_i = int(frequences[i]*n_quantile)
        c_k_children.extend([i+1]*number_children_class_i)
    return c_k_children

    Linear Regression¶

    Simple linear regression estimates the parameters of the line linking the response variable to the predictive variable, but it also makes it possible to evaluate whether this relationship is significant or not. For this, a T test is used to evaluate whether the slope is significantly different from 0 or not. However, the result of this test T is valid only if the following four hypotheses are satisfied:
    1. The relationship between the two continuous numeric variables is actually of linear form (at least roughly).
    2. The residuals of the linear regression are independent: "Lag plot" + Durbin-Watson
    3. The residuals of the linear regression are distributed according to a Normal distribution of average 0 (at least roughly): QQplot + Shapiro-Wilk
    4. The residuals of the linear regression are homogeneously distributed: "Residuals vs fitted plot" + Breusch-Pagan

    Statistical test: Verification of the assumption of normality of the law followed by residues¶

    In [81]:
    from scipy.stats import shapiro
 
def test_shapiro(model):
    stat, p = shapiro(model.resid)
    print('Statistics=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
    # interpret
    alpha = 0.05
    if p > alpha:
        print('Sample looks Gaussian (fail to reject H0)')
    else:
        print('Sample does not look Gaussian (reject H0)')

    def plot_qq_plot(model,title):
    # normalized residuals

    QQ = ProbPlot(model_norm_residuals)
    plot = QQ.qqplot(line='45', alpha=0.5, color='#4C72B0', lw=1)
    plot.axes[0].set_title('Normal Q-Q '+ title)
    plot.axes[0].set_xlabel('Quantiles of the normal law')

    import statsmodels.stats.api as sms

def test_breuschpagan(model):
    lagrange_multiplier_statistic, p_value, f_value, f_p_value  = sms.het_breuschpagan(regr1.resid, regr1.model.exog)
    print('Statistics=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (f_value, f_p_value))
    # interpret
    alpha = 0.05
    if f_p_value > alpha:
        print('Residue homogeneity assumption is not rejected.')
    else:
        print('Residue homogeneity assumption is rejected.')

    def plot_scale_location(model,title):
    # model values
    model_fitted_y = model.fittedvalues
    # normalized residuals
    model_norm_residuals = model.get_influence().resid_studentized_internal    
    # absolute squared normalized residuals
    model_norm_residuals_abs_sqrt = np.sqrt(np.abs(model_norm_residuals))
    
    plot = plt.figure()
    plt.scatter(model_fitted_y, model_norm_residuals_abs_sqrt, alpha=0.5);
    sns.regplot(model_fitted_y, model_norm_residuals_abs_sqrt,
                scatter=False,
                ci=False,
                lowess=True,
                line_kws={'color': 'red', 'lw': 1, 'alpha': 0.8});
    plot.axes[0].set_title('Scale-Location '+ title)
    plot.axes[0].set_xlabel('Fitted values')
    plot.axes[0].set_ylabel('$\sqrt{|Standardized Residuals|}$');
    plt.savefig('figure/Figure - Scale-Location.png', dpi=300)

    from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

def test_colinearite(model):
    variables = model.model.exog
    return [variance_inflation_factor(variables, i) for i in np.arange(1,variables.shape[1])]

    Percentage of influential outliers among all individuals studied¶

    In [86]:
    def pourcentage_outliers_influents(data, model):
    n, p = data.shape

    # To find Cook's distance, we execute this:
    (model_dist_cook, p_model_dist_cook)= model.get_influence().cooks_distance

    # Cook's distance threshold is n-p.
    seuil_dcook = 4/(n-p)

    # Number of outliers (having a Cook distance greater than Cook's threshold)
    model_nb_outliers = (model_dist_cook > seuil_dcook).sum()
    pourcentage_model_nb_outliers = model_nb_outliers/n

    print(round(100*pourcentage_model_nb_outliers,2),"% of individuals are influential outliers")

    Non parametric ANOVA¶

    In this situation of rejection of the assumptions of normality and homogeneity of the residues, it is possible to compare the means using a nonparametric ANOVA, or Kruskal-Wallis test.
    In [96]:
    country_kruskal = []
for code in final_data_sampled['country'].drop_duplicates():

    Out[96]:
    KruskalResult(statistic=853744.3269865265, pvalue=0.0)
    As the test value is less than 0.05, the assumption of equality of averages is rejected. It is therefore concluded that the average income of children in countries is different.

    Checking collinearity of variables¶

  • Prob (F-statistic) < 5%: The model is significant.
  • P-values: index_gini, gdpppp, c_k_parent: < 5%: The coefficients are significant with a 95% confidence interval.

    • By observing the regression coefficient associated with the Gini index, can we say that living in a more unequal country favors more people than it does not?

  • The child's income has the following expression:
    • ln (child_income) = const - 0.0188 x gini + 0.8575 x ln (gdpppp) + 0.0108 x c_k_parent
  • Middle income and constant parent class:
    • ln (income_child) = alpha - 0.0188 x gini where income_child = $ e ^ {alpha} $ / $ e ^ {0.0188gini} $
  • For a child from a country 1 more unequal than a country 2 (gini1> gini2), a country with the same average income, and having parents belonging to the same class:
    • income_enfant1 < income_child2 **It can not therefore be said that living in a more unequal country favors more people than it disadvantages. It's the contrary.** But how much? Increasing the Gini index by n amounts to dividing the child's income by $ e ^ {0.0188n} $.
    In [135]:
    print('In 2008, the Gini index of South Africa was', gini_2008[gini_2008['country_name']=='South Africa']['indice_gini'].sum())
print('In 2008, the Gini index of France was', gini_2008[gini_2008['country_name']=='France']['indice_gini'].sum())

    In 2008, the Gini index of South Africa was 63.0
In 2008, the Gini index of France was 33.0
    Assuming that the average income of France and the average income of South Africa are equal, for children with parents belonging to the same class: a child from South Africa will earn $ e ^ {0.0188 * (63 -33)} $ = 1.78 times less than a child of France.

  • The linear regression 1 with the average income and the Gini index of the country explains to 62% the variation of the income of the child.
  • The linear regression 2, by adding the income class of the parents, to 68% the variation of the incomes of the child.
    • This last model is the most powerful and can be used to predict the child's income, knowing the Gini index and the average income of the country, as well as the income class of his parents.
